  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming: The Easiest Coat in the Shop" imageAlt="Miniature Pinscher puppy getting a quick coat wipe-down" imageSrc={imgScene3} imagePosition="left">
      <p>Grooming a Min Pin is a weekly wipe with a soft brush or grooming mitt, an occasional bath, and done; the sleek coat polishes itself. There is no salon schedule, no mats, no coat blow, and in our climate no drying drama after rain. This is genuinely the lowest-grooming dog we carry, sharing the title with the smooth-coat Chihuahua.</p>
      <p>The maintenance budget goes to nails, which grow fast on a dog this active, and the daily tooth-brushing habit every small jaw needs. Both tools are in your starter kit, and both take minutes a week.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Min Pin Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Miniature Pinscher puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene4} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Min Pin goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. Health is a strong suit: the breed is robust and long-lived, which its 12-to-16-year expectancy reflects. The short list worth knowing: patellar luxation, the standard small-breed kneecap issue; Legg-Calvé-Perthes, a hip condition seen occasionally in small breeds; and dental crowding, met with the day-one brushing habit.</p>
      <p>The practical health work with a Min Pin is injury prevention rather than illness: this fearless breed will leap from heights it shouldn't and squeeze through gaps it found first. Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. See the <a href="/learn/puppy-health" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">puppy health checks explained</a> guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Min Pin's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Miniature Pinscher puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={imgScene5} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Min Pin inspects the premises, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person, including the escape-proofing check. Learn more about <a href="/delivery" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">how our free home delivery and setup works</a>.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm and predictable. A fixed feeding routine, the toilet pads where we placed them, and supervised exploration; assume anything reachable will be investigated and act accordingly.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks and the King settles into his territory. Book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer this week; early boundaries are everything with a clever, confident breed. See <a href="/free-training" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers</a>.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

